## Thread.Abort Migration to .NET 8

Your code has three patterns that won't work in .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`):

| Pattern Found | Replacement |
|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **`ThreadAbortException` catch → cleanup** | `OperationCanceledException` catch |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort`** | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| **`Thread.Abort()` in Stop()** | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can wake up
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces the ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — cooperative cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow.
                // Loop condition will exit naturally on next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals all token checks to stop

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
        // If still alive after Join, the thread is stuck in uncooperative code.
        // There is no .NET 8 equivalent of Abort — see pitfalls below.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

1. **`_running` → `CancellationToken`** — The volatile bool is replaced by `CancellationTokenSource` / `CancellationToken`, which integrates with `WaitHandle`, async APIs, and framework methods.

2. **`Thread.Abort()` → `_cts.Cancel()`** — Cancel is cooperative; the thread must check the token. `Thread.Join(timeout)` replaces `Thread.Sleep(2000)` and actually waits for the thread to exit.

3. **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` → `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (…)`** — The `when` guard ensures you only catch cancellations *you* initiated, not unrelated ones.

4. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` removed** — `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception; it doesn't auto-rethrow. No reset needed.

5. **`IDisposable` added** — `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks.

### Critical: Update GetNextItem

If `GetNextItem` blocks (e.g., on a queue), it **must** accept the token or cancellation will stall:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks forever, ignores cancellation
var item = queue.Take();

// AFTER — wakes up immediately when token is cancelled
var item = queue.Take(token); // BlockingCollection<T>.Take(CancellationToken)
```

If it uses `Thread.Sleep`, replace with:
```csharp
// BEFORE
Thread.Sleep(1000);

// AFTER — wakes on cancellation instead of sleeping the full duration
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000);
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---|---|
| **`GetNextItem` still blocks** | The #1 cause of "cancellation doesn't work." Every blocking call in the chain must accept the token. |
| **No `Abort` fallback exists** | If the thread is stuck in code you can't modify (native call, third-party lib), `Cancel()` won't help. Move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Always use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to avoid swallowing unrelated cancellations. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Wrap in `IDisposable` or `using`. Leaked CTS instances leak timers. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | It only fires at the next checkpoint. If `ProcessItem` runs for 30 seconds without checking the token, cancellation waits 30 seconds. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive steps inside `ProcessItem`. |
